🎯 SLIDE 1 — Registry Comparison (ECR vs JFrog)
Title:

Container Registry Comparison – ECR vs JFrog

📊 TABLE
Feature	Amazon ECR	JFrog Artifactory
Type	AWS-native container registry	Enterprise artifact platform
Ecosystem	AWS-only	Multi-cloud + on-prem
Integration	Tight with EKS, IAM, VPC	External integration required
Setup	Fully managed	Needs setup (SaaS/self-hosted)
Artifact Support	Containers only	Containers + Maven, npm, Helm, etc.
Security	IAM-based, Inspector integration	Role-based + Xray integration
CI/CD Integration	Basic	Advanced pipelines + automation
UI/UX	Basic	Rich developer-friendly UI
Scalability	Automatic	Depends on deployment
🎨 Visual Suggestion:
Left: AWS logo (ECR)
Right: JFrog logo
Arrow pointing to EKS cluster
🗣️ Speaker Notes:

ECR is simple and AWS-native. JFrog is broader and enterprise-focused.

🎯 SLIDE 2 — Registry Pros, Cons & Decision
Title:

Registry Trade-offs & Recommendation

📊 TABLE
Category	ECR	JFrog
Pros	Native to AWS, low ops, cheaper, IAM integration	Multi-cloud, advanced repos, supports all artifacts
Cons	AWS lock-in, limited features, container-only	Costly, complex, needs management
Cost	Pay per storage + transfer	License + infra + ops
Best Use Case	AWS EKS workloads	Enterprise artifact platform
🎯 Decision Box (Highlight)

👉 Recommended for us:

Use ECR for EKS workloads
Use JFrog only if multi-cloud/artifact needs exist
🎨 Visual Suggestion:
Green box → “ECR Recommended”
Yellow box → “JFrog Optional”
🗣️ Speaker Notes:

ECR fits AWS-first strategy. JFrog only if broader enterprise needs.

🎯 SLIDE 3 — Security Mapping (Current vs AWS)
Title:

Security Mapping – Current vs AWS

📊 TABLE
Security Layer	Current (OpenShift)	AWS (EKS)
Image Scanning	ACS	Inspector
Runtime Security	ACS	GuardDuty
Pre-build Scan	Jenkins/Xray	Same / optional
VM Scanning	Nessus	Separate (not EKS-specific)
Platform Type	Unified (ACS)	Split services
🎨 Visual Suggestion:

Flow diagram:

CI/CD → Image → ACS → Runtime
↓
CI/CD → ECR → Inspector → EKS → GuardDuty
🗣️ Speaker Notes:

ACS = all-in-one. AWS = split responsibilities.

🎯 SLIDE 4 — Inspector vs GuardDuty vs ACS
Title:

Security Tools Deep Comparison

📊 TABLE
Feature	Inspector	GuardDuty	ACS
Purpose	Image scanning	Runtime threat detection	Full platform
Scope	OS + package vulnerabilities	Process, network, behavior	Image + runtime + policy
Timing	Before deployment	After deployment	Both
Integration	ECR	EKS + AWS logs	Kubernetes-native
Management	Fully managed	Fully managed	Needs setup
Visibility	Limited	Medium	High (centralized)
🎯 Key Insight (Highlight Box)

👉 AWS = Split model
👉 ACS = Unified model

🎨 Visual Suggestion:
Split diagram:
Left: ACS (single box)
Right: Inspector + GuardDuty (2 boxes)
🗣️ Speaker Notes:

AWS splits security across tools; ACS combines everything.

🎯 SLIDE 5 — Security Strategy Decision
Title:

Security Strategy Recommendation

📊 TABLE
Approach	Tools	Pros	Cons	Fit for Us
AWS Native	Inspector + GuardDuty	Simple, low ops, scalable	Split tools, less K8s-native	⭐ Recommended
Kubernetes-native	ACS	Unified, consistent, powerful	Setup + cost	Optional
🎯 Decision Box

👉 Option 1 (Recommended):

Inspector + GuardDuty
Simple, AWS-aligned

👉 Option 2 (Alternative):

Keep ACS for consistency
🎨 Visual Suggestion:
Two columns:
AWS Native (✔ simple)
ACS (✔ control)
🗣️ Speaker Notes:

Choose based on simplicity vs control. Vendor recommends AWS-native.
